#: src/items.md:1
msgid "Items"
msgstr "項目"

#: src/items.md:3
msgid ""
"Items consist of the set of things permitted at the top level of a module. "
"However, Rust also allows some items to appear within some other types of "
"items, such as within a function. The same formatting conventions apply "
"whether an item appears at module level or within another item."
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:8
msgid ""
"`extern crate` statements must be first in a file. They must be ordered "
"alphabetically."
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:11
msgid ""
"`use` statements, and module _declarations_ (`mod foo;`, not `mod { ... }`) "
"must come before other items. Put imports before module declarations. "
"Version-sort each, except that `self` and `super` must come before any other "
"names."
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:16
msgid ""
"Don't automatically move module declarations annotated with `#[macro_use]`, "
"since that might change semantics."
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:19
msgid "Function definitions"
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:21
msgid ""
"In Rust, people often find functions by searching for `fn [function-name]`, "
"so the formatting of function definitions must enable this."
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:24
msgid "The proper ordering and spacing is:"
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:27
msgid "\"ABI\""
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:32
msgid "Avoid comments within the signature itself."
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:34
msgid ""
"If the function signature does not fit on one line, then break after the "
"opening parenthesis and before the closing parenthesis and put each argument "
"on its own block-indented line. For example,"
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:47
msgid "Note the trailing comma on the last argument."
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:49
msgid "Tuples and tuple structs"
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:51
msgid "Write the type list as you would a parameter list to a function."
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:53
msgid "Build a tuple or tuple struct as you would call a function."
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:55
msgid "Single-line"
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:64
msgid "Enums"
msgstr "列舉"

#: src/items.md:66
msgid "In the declaration, put each variant on its own line, block indented."
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:68
msgid ""
"Format each variant accordingly as either a struct (but without the `struct` "
"keyword), a tuple struct, or an identifier (which doesn't require special "
"formatting):"
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:83
msgid ""
"If a struct variant is [_small_](index.html#small-items), format it on one "
"line. In this case, do not use a trailing comma for the field list, but do "
"put spaces around each brace:"
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:93
msgid ""
"In an enum with multiple struct variants, if any struct variant is written "
"on multiple lines, use the multi-line formatting for all struct variants. "
"However, such a situation might be an indication that you should factor out "
"the fields of the variant into their own struct."
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:98
msgid "Structs and Unions"
msgstr "結構體與聯合體"

#: src/items.md:100
msgid ""
"Struct names follow on the same line as the `struct` keyword, with the "
"opening brace on the same line when it fits within the right margin. All "
"struct fields are indented once and end with a trailing comma. The closing "
"brace is not indented and appears on its own line."
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:112
msgid ""
"If and only if the type of a field does not fit within the right margin, it "
"is pulled down to its own line and indented again."
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:123
msgid ""
"Prefer using a unit struct (e.g., `struct Foo;`) to an empty struct (e.g., "
"`struct Foo();` or `struct Foo {}`, these only exist to simplify code "
"generation), but if you must use an empty struct, keep it on one line with "
"no space between the braces: `struct Foo();` or `struct Foo {}`."
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:128
msgid "The same guidelines are used for untagged union declarations."
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:139
msgid "Tuple structs"
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:141
msgid ""
"Put the whole struct on one line if possible. Separate types within the "
"parentheses using a comma and space. Don't use a trailing comma for a single-"
"line tuple struct. Don't put spaces around the parentheses or semicolon:"
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:149
msgid ""
"Prefer unit structs to empty tuple structs (these only exist to simplify "
"code generation), e.g., `struct Foo;` rather than `struct Foo();`."
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:152
msgid ""
"For more than a few fields (in particular if the tuple struct does not fit "
"on one line), prefer a proper struct with named fields."
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:155
msgid ""
"For a multi-line tuple struct, block-format the fields with a field on each "
"line and a trailing comma:"
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:165
msgid "Traits"
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:167
msgid ""
"Use block-indent for trait items. If there are no items, format the trait "
"(including its `{}`) on a single line. Otherwise, break after the opening "
"brace and before the closing brace:"
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:179
msgid ""
"If the trait has bounds, put a space after the colon but not before, and put "
"spaces around each `+`, e.g.,"
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:186
msgid ""
"Prefer not to line-break in the bounds if possible (consider using a `where` "
"clause). Prefer to break between bounds than to break any individual bound. "
"If you must break the bounds, put each bound (including the first) on its "
"own block-indented line, break before the `+` and put the opening brace on "
"its own line:"
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:203
msgid "Impls"
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:205
msgid ""
"Use block-indent for impl items. If there are no items, format the impl "
"(including its `{}`) on a single line. Otherwise, break after the opening "
"brace and before the closing brace:"
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:217
msgid ""
"Avoid line-breaking in the signature if possible. If a line break is "
"required in a non-inherent impl, break immediately before `for`, block "
"indent the concrete type and put the opening brace on its own line:"
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:229
msgid "Extern crate"
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:231
msgid "`extern crate foo;`"
msgstr "`extern crate foo;`"

#: src/items.md:233
msgid "Use spaces around keywords, no spaces around the semicolon."
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:235
msgid "Modules"
msgstr "模組"

#: src/items.md:246
msgid ""
"Use spaces around keywords and before the opening brace, no spaces around "
"the semicolon."
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:249
msgid "`macro_rules!`"
msgstr "`macro_rules!`"

#: src/items.md:251
msgid "Use `{}` for the full definition of the macro."
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:258
msgid "Generics"
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:260
msgid ""
"Prefer to put a generics clause on one line. Break other parts of an item "
"declaration rather than line-breaking a generics clause. If a generics "
"clause is large enough to require line-breaking, prefer a `where` clause "
"instead."
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:264
msgid ""
"Do not put spaces before or after `<` nor before `>`. Only put a space after "
"`>` if it is followed by a word or opening brace, not an opening "
"parenthesis. Put a space after each comma. Do not use a trailing comma for a "
"single-line generics clause."
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:275
msgid ""
"If the generics clause must be formatted across multiple lines, put each "
"parameter on its own block-indented line, break after the opening `<` and "
"before the closing `>`, and use a trailing comma."
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:286
msgid ""
"If an associated type is bound in a generic type, put spaces around the `=`:"
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:292
msgid "Prefer to use single-letter names for generic parameters."
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:294
msgid "`where` clauses"
msgstr "`where` 子句"

#: src/items.md:296
msgid "These rules apply for `where` clauses on any item."
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:298
msgid ""
"If immediately following a closing bracket of any kind, write the keyword "
"`where` on the same line, with a space before it."
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:301
msgid ""
"Otherwise, put `where` on a new line at the same indentation level. Put each "
"component of a `where` clause on its own line, block-indented. Use a "
"trailing comma, unless the clause is terminated with a semicolon. If the "
"`where` clause is followed by a block (or assignment), start that block on a "
"new line. Examples:"
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:339
msgid "// Note, no trailing comma.\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:340
msgid ""
"// Note that where clauses on `type` aliases are not enforced and should "
"not\n"
"// be used.\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:349
msgid ""
"If a `where` clause is very short, prefer using an inline bound on the type "
"parameter."
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:352
msgid ""
"If a component of a `where` clause does not fit and contains `+`, break it "
"before each `+` and block-indent the continuation lines. Put each bound on "
"its own line. E.g.,"
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:367
msgid "Type aliases"
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:369
msgid ""
"Keep type aliases on one line when they fit. If necessary to break the line, "
"do so before the `=`, and block-indent the right-hand side:"
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:374
msgid "// If multi-line is required\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:380
msgid ""
"When there is a trailing `where` clause after the type, and no `where` "
"clause present before the type, break before the `=` and indent. Then break "
"before the `where` keyword and format the clauses normally, e.g.,"
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:385
msgid "// With only a trailing where clause\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:393
msgid ""
"When there is a `where` clause before the type, format it normally, and "
"break after the last clause. Do not indent before the `=` to leave it "
"visually distinct from the indented clauses that precede it. If there is "
"additionally a `where` clause after the type, break before the `where` "
"keyword and format the clauses normally."
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:400
msgid "// With only a preceding where clause.\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:406
msgid "// Or with both a preceding and trailing where clause.\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:418
msgid "Associated types"
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:420
msgid ""
"Format associated types like type aliases. Where an associated type has a "
"bound, put a space after the colon but not before:"
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:427
msgid "extern items"
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:429
msgid ""
"When writing extern items (such as `extern \"C\" fn`), always specify the "
"ABI. For example, write `extern \"C\" fn foo ...` or `unsafe extern "
"\"C\" { ...}` and avoid `extern fn foo ...` and `unsafe extern { ... }`."
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:433
msgid "Imports (`use` statements)"
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:435
msgid ""
"Format imports on one line where possible. Don't put spaces around braces."
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:443
msgid "Large list imports"
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:445
msgid ""
"Prefer to use multiple imports rather than a multi-line import. However, "
"tools should not split imports by default."
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:448
msgid ""
"If an import does require multiple lines (either because a list of single "
"names does not fit within the max width, or because of the rules for nested "
"imports below), then break after the opening brace and before the closing "
"brace, use a trailing comma, and block indent the names."
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:454
msgid "// Prefer\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:457
msgid "// If necessary\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:461
msgid "// Note trailing comma\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:465
msgid "Ordering of imports"
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:467
msgid ""
"A _group_ of imports is a set of imports on the same or sequential lines. "
"One or more blank lines or other items (e.g., a function) separate groups of "
"imports."
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:470
msgid ""
"Within a group of imports, imports must be version-sorted. Groups of imports "
"must not be merged or re-ordered."
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:473
msgid "E.g., input:"
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:483
msgid "output:"
msgstr "輸出："

#: src/items.md:493
msgid ""
"Because of `macro_use`, attributes must also start a new group and prevent "
"re-ordering."
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:496
msgid "Ordering list import"
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:498
msgid "Names in a list import must be version-sorted, except that:"
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:499
msgid "`self` and `super` always come first if present, and"
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:500
msgid "groups and glob imports always come last if present."
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:502
msgid ""
"This applies recursively. For example, `a::*` comes before `b::a` but `a::b` "
"comes before `a::*`. E.g., `use foo::bar::{a, b::c, b::d, b::d::{x, y, z}, "
"b::{self, r, s}};`."
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:506
msgid "Normalisation"
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:508
msgid "Tools must make the following normalisations, recursively:"
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:510
msgid "`use a::self;` -> `use a;`"
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:511
msgid "`use a::{};` -> (nothing)"
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:512
msgid "`use a::{b};` -> `use a::b;`"
msgstr "`use a::{b};` -> `use a::b;`"

#: src/items.md:514
msgid ""
"Tools must not otherwise merge or un-merge import lists or adjust glob "
"imports (without an explicit option)."
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:517
msgid "Nested imports"
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:519
msgid ""
"If there are any nested imports in a list import, then use the multi-line "
"form, even if the import fits on one line. Each nested import must be on its "
"own line, but non-nested imports must be grouped on as few lines as possible."
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:523
msgid "For example,"
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:533
msgid "Merging/un-merging imports"
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:535
msgid "An example:"
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:538
msgid "// Un-merged\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:541
msgid "// Merged\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/items.md:546
msgid ""
"Tools must not merge or un-merge imports by default. They may offer merging "
"or un-merging as an option."
msgstr ""
